#Text=MY COUSIN FANNY
#Text=We do not keep Christmas now as we used to do in old Hanover .
#Text=We have not time for it , and it does not seem like the same thing .
#Text=Christmas , however , always brings up to me my cousin Fanny ; I suppose because she always was so foolish about Christmas .
#Text=My cousin Fanny was an old maid ; indeed , to follow St. Paul ’s turn of phrase , she was an old maid of the old maids .
#Text=No one who saw her a moment could have doubted it .
#Text=Old maids have from most people a feeling rather akin to pity -- a hard heritage .
#Text=They very often have this feeling from the young .

#Text=This must be the hardest part of all -- to see around them friends , each “ a happy mother of children , ” little ones responding to affection with the sweet caresses of childhood , whilst any advances that they , their aunts or cousins , may make are met with indifference or condescension .
#Text=My cousin
#Text=Fanny was no exception .
#Text=She was as proud as Lucifer ; yet she went through life -- the part that I knew of -- bearing the pity of the great majority of the people who knew her .
#Text=She lived at an old place called “ Woodside ” , which had been in the family for a great many years ; indeed , ever since before the Revolution .
#Text=The neighborhood dated back to the time of the colony , and Woodside was one of the old places .

#Text=My cousin Fanny ’s grandmother had stood in the door of her chamber with her large scissors in her hand , and defied Tarleton ’s red-coated troopers to touch the basket of old communion-plate which she had hung on her arm .

#Text=The house was a large brick edifice , with a pyramidal roof , covered with moss , small windows , porticos with pillars somewhat out of repair , a big , high hall , and a staircase wide enough to drive a gig up it if it could have turned the corners .

#Text=A grove of great forest oaks and poplars densely shaded it , and made it look rather gloomy ; and the garden , with the old graveyard covered with periwinkle at one end , was almost in front , while the side of the wood -- a primeval forest , from which the place took its name -- came up so close as to form a strong , dark background .
#Text=During the war the place , like most others in that neighborhood , suffered greatly , and only a sudden exhibition of spirit on Cousin Fanny ’s part saved it from a worse fate .

#Text=After the war it went down ; the fields were poor , and grew up in briers and sassafras , and the house was too large and out of repair to keep from decay , the ownership of it being divided between Cousin Fanny and other members of the family .
#Text=Cousin
#Text=Fanny had no means whatever , so that it soon was in a bad condition .
#Text=The rest of the family , as they grew up , went off , compelled by necessity to seek some means of livelihood , and would have taken Cousin
#Text=Fanny too if she would have gone ; but she would not go .

#Text=They did all they could for her , but she preferred to hang around the old place , and to do what she could with her “ mammy ” , and “ old Stephen ” , her mammy ’s husband , who alone remained in the quarters .
#Text=She lived in a part of the house , locking up the rest , and from time to time visited among her friends and relatives , who always received her hospitably .

#Text=She had an old piece of a mare ( which I think she had bought from Stephen ) , with one eye , three legs , and no mane or tail to speak of , and on which she lavished , without the least perceptible result , care enough to have kept a stable in condition . In a freak of humor she named this animal “ Fashion ” , after a noted racer of the old times , which had been raised in the county , and had beaten the famous Boston in a great race .
#Text=She always spoke of “ Fash ” with a tone of real tenderness in her voice , and looked after her , and discussed her ailments , which were always numerous , as if she had been a delicate child .

#Text=Mounted on this beast , with her bags and bundles , and shawls and umbrella , and a long stick or pole , she used occasionally to make the tour of the neighborhood , and was always really welcomed ; because , notwithstanding the trouble she gave , she always stirred things up .
#Text=As was said once , you could no more have remained dull where she was than you could have dozed with a chinkapin-burr down your back .
#Text=Her retort was that a chinkapin-burr might be used to rouse people from a lethargy ( she had an old maid ’s tongue ) .
#Text=By the younger members of the family she was always welcomed , because she furnished so much fun .

#Text=She nearly always fetched some little thing to her host -- not her hostess -- a fowl , or a pat of butter from her one old cow , or something of the kind , because , she said , “ Abigail had established the precedent , and she was ‘ a woman of good understanding’ -- she understood that feeding and flattery were the way to win men . ”

#Text=She would sometimes have a chicken in a basket hung on the off pummel of her old saddle , because at times she fancied she could not eat anything but chicken soup , and she did “ not wish to give trouble . ”
#Text=She used to give trouble enough ; for it generally turned out that she had heard some one was sick in the neighborhood , and she wanted the soup carried to her .
#Text=I remember how mad Joe got because she made him go with her to carry a bucket of soup to old Mrs. Ronquist .
